The paper deals with the problem of future prediction, which is a common topic in machine learning and artificial intelligence. The proposed approach involves the prediction of several samples of the future with a winner-takes-all loss and iterative grouping of samples to multiple modes. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG), which deals with the development of algorithms and models that can learn from data and make predictions. Additionally, the paper discusses how to evaluate predicted multimodal distributions, which is a common problem in computer vision (cs.CV) and robotics (cs.RO), where the future state of the environment needs to be predicted. Finally, the paper's focus on modeling uncertainty and multimodality suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Systems and Control (cs.SY).
